<h2>The Pizza City</h2>

<p>
Windsor, a town in Southern Ontario, is often overshadowed by Detroit and dismissed as lacking a distinct identity. Windsor is often referred to as the “Rose City” due to a campaign in the early 1960s. Windsor is also known for its automotive industry, with production at the Stellantis Chrysler and Ford Motor Company plants. Finally, Windsor often receives credit from historians for its role during Prohibition and for the development of major businesses such as Hiram Walker. Windsor's identity, history, and business notoriety extend beyond these three areas. Windsor is arguably a prominent pizza city with a rich, well-developed pizza industry that is incredibly unique. The early migration of Italian families in the 1900s to Canada and America highlighted how Italian communities established their culture in a new country. Windsor was a prosperous center for economic opportunity for Italian families, which would later encourage the pizza business. Businesses like Volcano and local pizza makers like Tony Ciaravino helped lay the foundation for the Windsor pizza industry as it exists today. From these, many modern pizzerias were established in Windsor and developed a family atmosphere, often run by immigrant families. These pizza locations connected those across Windsor, creating a loyal customer base who favoured the quality and experience of Windsor pizza. Even under pressure from big chains, local pizzerias have resisted the invasion and maintained their dominance in the pizza market. Today, local pizzerias continue to hold the legacy that makes Windsor the Pizza City. Although Windsor is a small city that many ignore, the Windsor Pizza Industry has given it a slice of identity in the competitive pizza community, separating it from the crust of American culture.
</p>



